nb2.changeNb(); #is now 2 and nb1.theNb is still 1

```

You could do something like this.
- `newInstance` just creates a copy of everything.
- Each `setter` returns the current object so other setters can be called as setters of the new object.
```
public class CopyAnInstance {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
       
       MyObj first = new MyObj(1,2,&quot;abc&quot;, List.of(&quot;A&quot;,&quot;B&quot;,&quot;C&quot;));
       MyObj second = first.newInstance().setA(10);
       System.out.println(first);
       System.out.println(second);
    }
}
```
prints
```
1, 2, abc, [A, B, C]
10, 2, abc, [A, B, C]
```
The class definition
```
class MyObj {
    private int a;
    private int b;
    private String s;
    private List&lt;String&gt; list;
    
    public MyObj(int a, int b, String s, List&lt;String&gt; list) {
        this.a = a;
        this.b = b;
        this.s = s;
        this.list = list;
    }
    
    public  MyObj newInstance() {
        return new MyObj(a,b,s,new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(list));
    }
    
    public MyObj setA(int val) {
        this.a = val;
        return this;
    }
    public MyObj setB(int val) {
        this.b = val;
        return this;
    }
    public MyObj setS(String val) {
        this.s = val;
        return this;
    }
    
    public MyObj setList(List&lt;String&gt; list) {
        this.list = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(list);
        return this;
    }
    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return &quot;%d, %d, %s, %s&quot;.formatted(a,b,s,list);
    }
}
```

**Considerations:**
- Be careful when copying hierarchical lists of mutable objects.  Each accessible and changeable object must be newly instantiated, otherwise you are passing references which can affect the source objects if their copied instances are altered.
- Immutable objects can just be passed as is.
- So can immutable lists (e.g. List.of) as long as the items themselves are immutable (per the first bullet). In spite of `List.of` being immutable and containing immutable strings I created a new mutable list.  Handling details like this are up to you.  This is just an example of one possibility.
- If your arguments to your class have primitive arrays or the arrays contain immutable objects, then cloning is a good way to copy them.
```
int[] a = {1,2,3,4};
int[] b = a.clone(); // an exact copy of &#39;a&#39; but a completely different instance.

